  "bib_entries": {
    "44126087": {
      "title": "Replacement of Dichloromethane within Chromatographic Purification: A Guide to Alternative Solvents",
      "abstract": "Replacement of dichloromethane as the bulk medium within chromatographic purification has been evaluated with a broad range of molecules containing functionality common within Medicinal Chemistry programmes. Analysis of the data set has generated a set of general guidelines to assist in the selection of alternative solvents for CH2Cl2 as the bulk media in these ubiquitously employed processes."
    },
    "44185458": {
      "title": "Evaluation of Alternative Solvents in Common Amide Coupling Reactions: Replacement of Dichloromethane and N,N-Dimethylformamide",
      "abstract": "formation is the single most common synthetic transformation used within medicinal chemistry. Indeed, several studies have demonstrated the prevalence of this particular transformation within the pharmaceutical sector: MacDonald\u2019s analysis of the GlaxoSmithKline (GSK) Respiratory Centre of Excellence for Drug Discovery revealed that 17% of all reaction types conducted in array (focused library) format were to prepare amide or sulfonamide moieties. 3 Similarly, Roughley\u2019s analysis of the most common reactions used within synthetic medicinal chemistry research across three of the largest pharmaceutical companies (GSK, AstraZeneca, and Pfizer) indicated that N-acylation to prepare amides ranked 1st for frequency of use, accounting for 16% of all reactions performed and with the amide linkage present in 54% of the compound set analysed. 4"
